🛠️ Step-by-Step Implementation Guide
Phase 1: Git Security Configuration
To protect sensitive API tokens and development folders, create a file named .gitignore at the absolute root of your workspace folder and populate it with the following rules:

Plaintext
# Ignore the environment credentials file
arduino_wifi_sensor/.env

# Ignore the Python virtual environment folder
.venv/
Tip: Once saved, the green status indicator (U) next to your .env file inside VS Code will disappear or turn gray, confirming that Git is successfully ignoring it.

Phase 2: Edge Hardware Firmware Setup
1. Add ESP8266 Architecture Support to Arduino IDE
Because the ESP8266 is an independent third-party chipset manufactured by Espressif Systems, its configuration libraries must be linked manually into your compiler environment:

In the Arduino IDE application menu, open Settings... (Cmd + ,).

Locate the Additional Boards Manager URLs text field and paste this URL:
http://arduino.esp8266.com/stable/package_esp8266com_index.json

Click OK.

Open the Boards Manager tool on the left-hand vertical sidebar (chip icon).

Search for esp8266 and click Install on the esp8266 by ESP8266 Community distribution suite.

2. Flash the Firmware Code
In the board dropdown selector at the top tool bar, select Select Other Board and Port.

Search for NodeMCU 1.0 (ESP-12E Module) on the left.

Check /dev/cu.usbserial-210 Serial Port (USB) on the right and click OK.

Paste the following code into your sketch window and click Upload (→):

C++
#include <ESP8266WiFi.h>

extern "C" {
  #include "user_interface.h"
}

void sniffer_callback(uint8_t *buffer, uint16_t length) {
  if (length > 12) {
    Serial.print("PKT:");
    Serial.print(length);
    Serial.print(":");
    for (int i = 0; i < min((int)length, 50); i++) {
      if (buffer[i] < 0x10) Serial.print("0");
      Serial.print(buffer[i], HEX);
    }
    Serial.println(); 
  }
}

void setup() {
  Serial.begin(115200);
  delay(500);
  Serial.println("\\n🛰️ Hardware Sniffer Initialized.");
  WiFi.disconnect();
  wifi_set_opmode(STATION_MODE);
  wifi_set_channel(6); 
  wifi_promiscuous_enable(0);
  wifi_set_promiscuous_rx_cb(sniffer_callback);
  wifi_promiscuous_enable(1);
}

void loop() {
  delay(10); 
}
Phase 3: Python Environment Alignment & Libraries Installation
To ensure commands run within your user scope instead of the strict system-level Xcode paths on macOS, update your libraries within your active terminal shell.

Run the module-level installation array command to download your prerequisite tool chains:

Bash
python3 -m pip install pyserial elasticsearch python-dotenv
Phase 4: Local Bridge Configuration (.env)
Inside your arduino_wifi_sensor subdirectory, create a configuration file named exactly .env. Populate it with your target cluster targets.

Code snippet
ELASTIC_CLOUD_ID=your_deployment_name:alphanumeric_hash_string...
ELASTIC_API_KEY=your_base64_encoded_elastic_cloud_api_key...
ARDUINO_USB_PORT=/dev/cu.usbserial-210
Note: Do not wrap key values in quotation marks or append extra spaces around the equals (=) operators.

Phase 5: Python Bridge Engine Implementation (sniffer_bridge.py)
Create your bridge engine script inside the arduino_wifi_sensor folder. This handles raw ingestion and maps documents directly to the Elasticsearch API framework.

Python
import os
import sys
import serial
import datetime
from dotenv import load_dotenv  
from elasticsearch import Elasticsearch  

load_dotenv()

ELASTIC_CLOUD_ID = os.getenv("ELASTIC_CLOUD_ID")
ELASTIC_API_KEY = os.getenv("ELASTIC_API_KEY")  

if not ELASTIC_CLOUD_ID or not ELASTIC_API_KEY:
    print("❌ Error: Missing ELASTIC_CLOUD_ID or ELASTIC_API_KEY in your .env file!")
    sys.exit(1)

es = Elasticsearch(
    cloud_id=ELASTIC_CLOUD_ID,
    api_key=ELASTIC_API_KEY  
)

ARDUINO_USB_PORT = os.getenv("ARDUINO_USB_PORT")
if not ARDUINO_USB_PORT:
    print("❌ Error: ARDUINO_USB_PORT is not set in your .env file!")
    sys.exit(1)

ser = serial.Serial(ARDUINO_USB_PORT, 115200, timeout=1)
print("🚀 Scanning the airwaves... Press Ctrl+C to stop.")

while True:
    try:
        line = ser.readline().decode('utf-8', errors='ignore').strip()
        print(f"Raw USB Data: '{line}'")
        
        if line.startswith("PKT:"):
            parts = line.split(":")
            if len(parts) >= 3:
                pkt_len = parts[1]
                raw_hex = parts[2]
                
                log_document = {
                    "@timestamp": datetime.datetime.utcnow().isoformat() + "Z",
                    "packet": {
                        "length": int(pkt_len),
                        "payload_hex": raw_hex[:100]
                    },
                    "sensor": {
                        "device": "arduino_esp8266",
                        "interface": "ambient_wifi"
                    }
                }
                
                es.index(index="logs-wifi", document=log_document)
                print(f"Captured packet size {pkt_len} bytes -> Sent to Elastic.")
    except KeyboardInterrupt:
        print("\\nStopping scan.")
        break
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"Error parsing data: {e}")
📈 Running and Monitoring the Pipeline
Port Release Check: Ensure you close the Arduino IDE Serial Monitor or any lingering terminal miniterms so the USB port is free.

Execute Ingestion: Navigate to your bridge directory and run the engine:

Bash
python3 sniffer_bridge.py
Gracefully Terminating: To safely shut down the pipeline and clear port allocations, use Ctrl + C inside your active terminal window. (Avoid Ctrl + Z, which suspends the script without letting it drop the hardware socket handle).

📊 Mapping Data in Kibana
To transform the raw streaming indices into searchable security views:

Log into your Elastic Cloud Console and navigate into Kibana.

Select Discover from the main navigation interface.

Select Create Data View.

Set the name to Wi-Fi Traffic and define the target index matching pattern precisely to: logs-wifi*

Click Save Data View to Kibana.

You can now immediately start tracking packet length mutations, graphing traffic density distributions, or filtering hex payloads to identify structural changes in nearby networks!
"""

